.TH "do_mem_probe" 9 "do_mem_probe" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
do_mem_probe \- validate a memory region for PCMCIA use
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" do_mem_probe
.BI "(struct pcmcia_socket *s "  ","
.BI "u_long base "  ","
.BI "u_long num "  ","
.BI "int fallback (struct pcmcia_socket *s# struct resource *res# unsigned int *value) "  ","
.BI "int fallback (struct pcmcia_socket *s# struct resource *res# unsigned int *value) "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "s" 12
PCMCIA socket to validate
.IP "base" 12
start address of resource to check
.IP "num" 12
size of resource to check
.IP "value" 12
-- undescribed --
.IP "value" 12
-- undescribed --
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
\fBdo_mem_probe\fP checks a memory region for use by the PCMCIA subsystem.
To do so, the area is split up into sensible parts, and then passed
into the \fI\fP\fBvalidate\fP function. Only if \fI\fP\fBvalidate\fP and \fI\fP\fBfallback\fP fail,
the area is marked as unavaibale for use by the PCMCIA subsystem. The
function returns the size of the usable memory area.
